The Effect of Chinas Huai River Policy on Air Pollution

In this empirical project, you will use a regression discontinuity design to estimate the causal effect of Huai River Policy on air pollution.

The Stata data file huairiver.dta consists of geographic, weather, and air quality information for 161 cities in China. These data were originally used in Ebenstein et al.(2017). The life expectancy variables used in the original paper are confidential and not available. For this empirical project, we will focus on the impact of the Huai River Policy on PM10 air pollution.

Introdution

Particulate matter is harmful, invisible to the naked eye, and has negative health consequences worth looking into. As the world expands through globalization and outsourcing, more pollution is being emitted to the environment, adding to the aggregated amount of particulate matter. This type of pollution is made up of non-decomposable, tiny chemical atoms. Once any particle enters your body, it does not come out, so prevention is the only sure fire way to maintain health status. The health effects of inhaling this airborne pollution have been found to be robustly associated with elevated risk of heart disease, stroke, and lung cancer. Questions regarding the health effects of PM and its appropriate regulation continue to be of tremendous scientific and policy relevance, because it is apparent that the existing evidence has not convinced countries to adopt and enforce tough emission standards.

Background Information

For this Regression Discontinuity study to be possible, the overlap assumption must hold wherein we are given both treated and untreated units for each level of \(X_i\) This is also known as the Common Support Assumption. (we need a y for every x treatment and control). Now, we can declare that under the CIA and Common Support Assumption, the causal effect is given by the difference in group means conditional on \(X_i\) (for each value of \(X_i = x\)). Because treated and untreated units differ only in terms of \(X_i\) (from the CIA) and because we have enough data to make \(_\) comparisons for all possible \(x\) levels (from the Common Support Assumption), the difference in outcomes between the treated and untreated group is the causal effect.

We can also do selection on observable methods using regressions since we are assuming constant treatment effect:

\(Y_i = a + (b)D_i + (c)X_i + E_i\)

where

\(a\) is a constant \(b\) is the treatment effect \(D_i\) is the treatment dummy (1 = treatment, 0 = control) \(c\) is the coefficient for the \(X_i\) of interest \(X_i\)s are the determinants of the outcome without treatment \(E_i\) is the error term

With random assignment, potential outcomes are independent of the treatment status. So in this case, if our treatment is completely random, we do not have to worry about the characteristics of \(X_i\) if they are not determined or influenced by the treatment. This means we do not have a bad control group as counterfactuals for our treatment group. The partial effect of treatment on the outcome is given when we regress our outcome variable \(Y_i\) on \(X_i\).

graphically, conditional expectation function is the expected value of outcome when units are treated, conditional on some controlled level of \(X_i\).

X is the only source of omitted variable selection bias, if we assume this x is the correct control variables, then our treatment should be random, and then controlling for x solves our selection bias problem. Using this regression technique, we get our causal estimate.

Background of Article

This paper estimates the effect of sustained exposure to particulate matter smaller than 10 m (PM10) on life expectancy with recent data from China. This quasiexperimental research design is based on Chinas Huai River Policy. The policy was instituted during the 1950s when economic resources were allocated through central planning and dictated that areas to the north of the Huai River received free or highly subsidized coal for indoor heating. This led to the construction of a coal-powered centralized heating infrastructure only in cities north of the Huai River, and no equivalent system is in cities to the south; Now China is left with very different rates of indoor heating north and south of the Huai River. With this knowledge in mind, we can expect to see a discontinuity when we run our regression. The authors estimates imply that bringing all of China into compliance with its Class I standards for PM10 would save 3.7 billion life-years. Overall, they estimate that the Huai River Policy generates an increase in PM10 exposure of 41.7 g/m3 [95% confidence interval (95% CI) = 16.467.0] and a decline of 3.1 years (95% CI = 1.34.9) in life expectancy just to the north of the river.

Questions

1. Explain why a simple comparison of air pollution in northern cities versus southern cities would not measure the causal effect of the Huai River Policy. Explain how did the Ebenstein et al.paper overcome this problem by using a regression discontinuity design.

A simple comparison of air pollution in China would not measure the causal effect of the Huai River Policy. This is due to the fact that the new policy created immediate effects in geographical location wherein the Chinese government held high restrictions on migration. The researchers decided to choose a RD design given the fact that previous pollution research had many limitations that would affect their analysis. The Ebenstein et al.paper discusses these limitations, and then describes their plan of action.

Empirical studies exploit limitations that have plagued the existing evidence linking health to air pollution especially at the high concentrations that prevail in many of todays developing countries. For one, the literature is almost entirely composed of observational studies that compare populations across locations with varying exposure to pollution. These studies are likely to confound air pollution with unobserved determinants of health that are correlated with pollution exposure (e.g., income, hospital quality, water pollution). The already available evidence is largely based on examinations of populations exposed to the modest levels of PM that are commonly observed in developed countries, where reliable pollution and health data are more readily available. PM concentrations in many developing countries (like India and China) are 510 times higher than in developed countries; consequently, the existing evidence has little empirical relevance for these countries if there is a nonlinear relationship between health and pollution. The most important questions about pollution center on the impacts of sustained exposurehowever, there have been few opportunities to measure long-run exposure to air pollution. Therefore, these studies have at least one of the following limitations: they (i) exploit observational variation in PM, (ii) use small samples, (iii) assume no selective migration, or (iv) focus on low levels of pollution found in the United States. As a consequence, the existing literature focuses on shorter-run variation in PM exposure and often examines outcomes (e.g., hospitalization, infant outcomes) that are only indirectly related to longer-run outcomes, like life expectancy. This paper estimates the effect of sustained exposure to particulate matter smaller than 10 m (PM10) on life expectancy with recent data from China and, in so doing, addresses each of the previous literatures limitations.

The quasiexperimental research design is based on Chinas Huai River Policy. The policy was instituted during the 1950s when economic resources were allocated through central planning and dictated that areas to the north of the Huai River received free or highly subsidized coal for indoor heating. This led to the construction of a coal-powered centralized heating infrastructure only in cities north of the Huai River, and no equivalent system is in cities to the south; the legacy of that policy is evident even today, with very different rates of indoor heating north and south of the Huai River. Consequently, the findings are derived from a regression discontinuity (RD) design based on distance from the Huai River.

The amount of air pollution in the north versus the south would give us approximate levels of the air pollution there. It would yield two mean, aggregated numbers divided between the north and the south. However, since there are numerous confounders for air pollution, we cannot relate air pollution levels to a policys enactment directly. The policy banned heating in the south during the winter because it was too expensive for the Chinese government, so if we were to base our causal analysis of this policy just on air pollution levels, we would probably think that the south decreased air pollution. Aggregating the mean of the north and aggregating the mean of the south, separately, and then finding the distance between would be a poor representation of the Huai River Policy. There would be too many omitted variables that could also be accounting for the observed differences in air pollution between the northern and southern cities.

This is because there are bias variables \(X_i\) that we must control for in our regression analysis.

Not to mention, over a whole country, these Chinese cities may not be demographically comparable. Disparities exist between cities that are far away from the river. The Ebenstein et al.paper was able to overcome this problem through regression discontinuity by making the assignment variable distance from Huai River. They test the effects just north and just south of the river, leaving no room for doubt.

2. Explain what is the outcome variable and what is the assignment variable in Fig.2 of the Ebenstein et al.paper?

Figure 2 given in the Ebenstein et al.paper was constructed using a Regression Discontinuity Design from a data extract from the Chinese Disease Surveillance Points (DSP) system recorded throughout the 1990s and beyond. We are assuming that the Huai River Policy only influences treatment where the probability of treatment rises at some threshold, but being above or below the threshold does not fully determine treatment status. With this running assumption, we have met the required Regression Discontinuitys Identification assumption. We separately estimate the following parametric equations to test for the impacts of the Huai River Policy on PM10 concentrations, and on life expectancy in China:

by local linear regression using the parametric RD approach:

\(PM_j =_0 + _1N_j + f(L_j)+N_jf(L_j)+X_j +u_j\)
\(Y_j =_0 + _1N_j +f(L_j) + N_jf(L_j)+ X_j +E_j\)

where

\(j\) references a DSP location in China
\(PM_j\) is the average annual ambient concentration of PM10 in location j over the period 20042012
\(Y_j\) is a measure of location js mortality rate (or) \(Y_j\) is a yearly measure of life expectancy at birth \(N_j\) is an indicator variable equal to one for locations that are north of the Huai River line
\(f(L_j)\) is a polynomial in degrees north of the Huai River that is interacted with \(N_j\) (chosen based on goodness of fit criteria) such that \(L_j\) is within \(h\) latitude degrees of the Huai River.
\(X_j\) is a vector of the demographic and city characteristics other than air quality that are associated with mortality rates
The outcome variable of interest is life expectancy and pm10 concentration levels. The assignment variable is northern location in relation to the Huai River, grouped into 154 DSL locations.

3. What is a binned scatter plot? Explain how it is constructed. Hint: Binscatter plot is covered in week1s lecture.

A binned scatterplot displays the relationship between the x axis variable and the y axis outcome variable by grouping along the x axis. Its where the data points are grouped into bins, and an aggregate statistic is used to summarize each bin. A binned scatter plot is a more scalable alternative to the standard scatter plot. The data points are grouped into bins, and an aggregate statistic is used to summarize each bin. When working on a large dataset, scatterplots themselves might become difficult to read, especially if you are looking for concentrations (densities) to judge the relationship and you have many observations that have the same or very similar values (overplotted points). A standard plot, displays a marker for every data point. To produce a binned plot, we have to group the x axis into subgroups with only one average observation to represent the whole x interval range per bin. For our analysis, we want to bin the distance from the Huai River through intervals of 1 degree

4. Graphical regression discontinuity analysis.

a. Draw a binned scatter plot to visualize how PM10 changes at the Huai River line. Display fitted lines (linear, or quadratic, or whatever functional form you see fit) based on what you see in the data.

Replicating Figure 2 of the paper, we depict how exposure to PM10 increases significantly at the Huai River, but pollution exists south and north of the river, making our context naturally analogous to a fuzzy RD, where the ratio is estimated as the ratio of two sharp discontinuities; in practice, we use the optimal bandwidth for life expectancy as the bandwidth for both life expectancy and PM10 concentration level.

Graphical Interpretation

First off, graphically, we can see that we do not have an explicit sharp regression discontinuity designwe have a fuzzy RD design. We can see this near our cutoff of x=0 distance from the Huai River, wherein some variables line of best fit seem to seamlessly match up, or have too messy of data points to classify it as sharp. We begin the analysis graphically with an assessment of the Huai River Policys impact on pollution. We have plots for PM10 at DSP locations against their degrees north of the Huai River line. The points in represent the average PM10 concentration across DSP locations within 1-latitude distance bins from the Huai River.

Although in the article, the authors were able to include life expectancy data and population size and we do not have that access. Thus, our binned scatterplot does not have each circles size proportional to the population at the DSP locations within the relevant bin. The plotted line of best fit is generated by using a kernel-weighted local linear regression on either side of the riversimilar to a nonparametric RD approach. This is estimated with a triangular kernel and bandwidth chosen by the method prescribed by Imbens and Kalyanaraman. We see a discontinuous change in ambient PM10 concentrations to the north of the river, indicating the Huai River Policy increased PM10 concentrations by about \(42 g/m3\).

5. Regression analysis. Run the regressions that correspond to your three graphs in 4a and 4b to quantify the discontinuities that you see in the data. Report a 95% confidence interval for each of these estimates. (more written about this in the assignment)

We read in the paper how the authors defined bandwidth selection. When determining bandwidth for replication, we got this bandwidth interval output of 5.6 to 9.29 using the IK selection through the rdrobust outdated package. Given this selection, we intuitively can discard it. Our bandwidth should include the cutoff point of 0, so that we do not drop outside observations that include the most detrimental part.

Using the package rdrobutthis command now allows for covariate-adjusted point estimation and covariate-adjusted robust bias-corrected inference. In addition, this command now allows for different heteroskedasticity-robust (heteroskedasticity-consistent k class or HCk class) and clusterrobust variance estimation methods. When mean squared error (MSE)optimal bandwidths are used, the resulting point estimator for the RD treatment effect is MSE optimal. When coverage error-rate (CER) optimal bandwidths are used, the resulting confidence intervals (CIs) for the RD treatment effect are CERoptimal.

The Regression in Regression Discontinuity:

Our goal is to estimate the diff in outcomes for just-treated vs.just-untreated. \(^^ =[_(1)_(0)|_=]=lim[[(1)_=]]lim[[_(0)|_=]]\)

We implement this by comparing average outcomes just below and above the cutoff

\(^^ = =1;+=0;\)

Where \(+\) is the bandwidth which were close to c.the variable name is h.

This leads to the regression-based RD:

\(Y_=+_+_\) for \(+\) where \(_=1(_)\)

This means were only looking at observations that are very close to our cutoff of c = 0.

6. Recall that any quasi experiment requires an identification assumption to make it as good as an experiment. What is the identification assumption for regression discontinuity design? Explain whether your graphs in 4b are consistent with that assumption.

The identification assumption for regression discontinuity design is that a change in the treatment is the only reason for discrete jumps in the outcome variable around the cutoff (which is where the discontinuity occurs). Unfortunately, this assumption is impossible to prove, but looking at the graphs should tell us whether or not the assumption holds. If it appears that the data are manipulated around the cutoff (that participants in the study were able to self-select into groups) or there is not a smooth transition of the data before and after the cutoff, then the assumption does not hold.

7. Another type of validity test for regression discontinuity design is the manipulation test. Do we need to worry about manipulation in this study context? Explain why or why not. If you believe a manipulation test should be done, report such a test.

For a manipulation test, we are assuming that bandwidth(how far apart an observation is from the cutoff) is as good as randomly assigned in the negihborhood of \(c=0\). By looking at the distribution of \(X_i\), we gather a TRUE or FALSE result from our Manipulation test. If the result comes back TRUE (i.e., we can assume that \(X_i - c\) replicates randomization in the bandwidth of \(c\). If we assume this is true, then units of observation cannot be resorted in the bandwidth around \(c=0\).

In general, we have to use a manipulation when the participants of the study can change whether or not they are in the control and the treatment group on their own. This is not an issue in this study because our assignment variable is the location of the Huai River, which is very difficult to manipulate. Manipulation occurs when participants in the study are able to change their situation just enough that they make it into the treatment group - they manipulate the results. In this case, the location of the Huai River is the assignment variable. For this reason, a manipulation test is not necessarythe Huai River cannot choose to move 1 degree north or south, and we know that Chinese citizens are under lockdown with their Chinese government wherein moving is not a feasible option. So if the river cannot move and the people cannot move, we have exceeding reason to not do a manipulation test.

8. Consider the placebo test in Fig. 4 of the Ebenstein et al.paper.

a. Explain the logic of the placebo test underlying Fig. 4. Why did the authors estimate regression discontinuity using false locations of the Huai River? What do the results of this test tell us?

The purpoe of the regression using the false location was to prove the exact cutoff threshold was sound, immobile, strict and in direct response to the Huai River Policy implemented. The main reason for implementing a placebo test when doing an RD study is to ensure that the cutoff studied is the only reason for the discontinuity in the datanot an accident or coincidence. By testing various placebo cutoffs from -5 to 5 degrees latitude away from the Huai River, we find whether the differences in the PM10 levels between the north and south of sides of the Huai river actually have a discontinuity directly at the cutoff (the direct location of the river). This tells us that the policy is causal and the results of the study are not "not just the general area, but for the explicit north/south location. When considering this, the authors found that the only statistically significant results occurred at the Huai River line. This indicates that the differences in PM10 levels could only be attributed to the Huai River Policyallowing us to establish a causal inference.

Conclusion

The analysis indicates that PM10 exposure causes people to live substantially shorter and sicker lives at the concentrations present today in China and other developing countries. From the Micheal Greenstones presentation speech on this study, we gather further analysis than our data allowed for. Greenstone was able to report elevated mortality rates are concentrated among cardiorespiratory causes of death, whereas there is little evidence of a difference in mortality rates for causes that are not plausibly related to air pollution. Henceforth, air pollution and particulate matter are imperative problems that must be solved in order for the health and well being of Chinese citizens to improve.
